Ah! noli. “ Ah, do not, Parmen03 as if you had not much rather tell this secret, than I hear it !'’ This seems to be no more than an ironical reply, intimating that she knew Parmeno too well, not to be satisfied that he was as impatient to impart the secret, as she was to know it. Yet Donatus remarks, that Philotis pretends that she has no fondness, no desire to know what she had asked: and that she thinks to persuade him by this, that as she had little curiosity, she was consequently one that might be safely trusted with a secret; for curiosity is almost always a sure sign osan incessant talker, that cannot retain any thing.
